1
00:00:02,004 --> 00:00:19,271
namo tassa bhagavato hara-hato samma-sambhodassam namo tassa bhagavato hara-hato samma-sambhodassam

2
00:00:20,027 --> 00:00:32,521
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambhodassa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:34,884 --> 00:00:39,329
So I've chosen this topic of love and relationship.

4
00:00:39,348 --> 00:00:49,039
Well, as you know, huge amounts of literature are written on love from philosophers, psychotherapists, self-helpers,

5
00:00:50,774 --> 00:01:11,685
all religions so i don't think i'll be covering everything but i i just want to mention one of you know a few of the essentials really so this is just love in general it's not specific i'm not going to talk about um parental love or falling in love all that sort of stuff

6
00:01:15,478 --> 00:01:22,228
So I think the first thing that always I find important is just this sense of care.

7
00:01:23,611 --> 00:01:27,055
You know, love is a little bit abused, the word love itself.

8
00:01:28,418 --> 00:01:31,862
But it's just understanding that interconnectedness we have.

9
00:01:32,322 --> 00:01:39,373
And it's funny that, you know, with Covid and all that, a lot of people rediscovered neighbourliness.

10
00:01:40,355 --> 00:01:43,900
And I think this is really part of this

11
00:01:44,167 --> 00:01:57,787
Neil Gaiman, Neoliberal thing you know the most people think of neoliberalism as a operating system and economic operating system, based on the market, but actually it's an ideology, you know.

12
00:01:58,578 --> 00:02:26,862
it's on the understanding that everything moves if everybody can just be an entrepreneurial individual and what it does is it it excites my greed to get things and have experience to get lots of money and by doing that of course I see you as a competitor so this is this is the system we're in we're in a system that you know supports greed and

13
00:02:27,282 --> 00:02:33,858
Competitiveness, it's not about coordination, it's not about interconnectedness.

14
00:02:33,877 --> 00:02:38,068
And I think this manifests clearly now with this COVID.

15
00:02:38,301 --> 00:03:02,233
because you know the rich countries just like individuals are just looking after themselves and to hell with everybody else but unfortunately the interconnectedness is biting back and I'm hoping that it has some effect on the actual system that we're under at the moment but just that sense of caring for somebody you know

16
00:03:03,444 --> 00:03:26,348
not talking about people who are sick or need help but just a general attitude of of uh looking after people being aware of their of their needs no matter what it is you know caring for them i think that's a really sort of important part of that of that whole syndrome that we call love

17
00:03:27,896 --> 00:03:37,606
And if we don't do that, if we don't have that sort of attitude, then I think we can shade off into controlling people, using them.

18
00:03:37,787 --> 00:03:45,474
I mean, abuse is at the far end, but you can also just use people, just for your own benefit.

19
00:03:48,397 --> 00:03:52,943
Sort of a presumption that they will help you, but you don't have to help them.

20
00:03:55,387 --> 00:04:05,281
So I think that really undermines a relationship when a person finds that they've been used.

21
00:04:05,861 --> 00:04:15,235
I think the other thing is a sort of kindness expressed through a certain affection.

22
00:04:16,447 --> 00:04:25,238
You know, we manifest that with hugging and holding hands and hand on heart, you know, tone of voice, all that sort of stuff.

23
00:04:26,300 --> 00:04:34,012
I mean, the danger is it sort of becomes a bit mawkish, bit sentimental, you know, huggy-wuggy, touchy-feely stuff.

24
00:04:35,314 --> 00:04:40,161
But I think it's important that there's a sort of expression of affection.

25
00:04:41,642 --> 00:04:43,365
And I don't know about you, but

26
00:04:44,442 --> 00:04:56,581
When I remember acts of unkindness that I've committed, there's always a sort of bitter sorrow that goes with it.

27
00:04:56,680 --> 00:04:59,384
How could I have behaved like that?

28
00:05:01,327 --> 00:05:05,435
And all that really just depends on this sense of being kind.

29
00:05:05,894 --> 00:05:07,598
It's a lovely word, kind.

30
00:05:09,838 --> 00:05:22,182
And when we put these two together and we wonder about how to live with other people, sharing spaces, whether it's intimate or just in an office, doesn't really matter.

31
00:05:23,223 --> 00:05:30,918
And there's this occasion in the scriptures where the Buddha comes across three Arahats living together.

32
00:05:31,101 --> 00:05:40,218
I think their name, I was trying to find it, I just couldn't find the passage, but I think they're called the Anarudas after the chief monk who was with them.

33
00:05:40,798 --> 00:05:43,444
And he asked them, how did they live so peacefully together?

34
00:05:44,285 --> 00:05:52,839
And he says, well, when I get up in the morning, I say to myself, what if I put aside what I want to do and do what the others want to do?

35
00:05:53,966 --> 00:05:57,892
And of course, if everybody says that, then you have this wonderful harmony.

36
00:05:58,494 --> 00:06:01,459
But if you're the only one who's saying it, then you'll probably get used.

37
00:06:03,562 --> 00:06:21,831
So it's a case of if you're with somebody, it doesn't matter where it is, as I say, the office or an intimate, just to get that feeling in the group that you're prepared to put aside what you want to do for what somebody else wants to do if it's more beneficial.

38
00:06:23,666 --> 00:06:53,589
mean it could even happen sort of on holiday you know where you've decided to go here and somebody else has decided to go there and there's a big rumpus over which one to do you know but that doesn't necessarily have to happen if if people have the attitude of putting aside what they want in other words you know not being attached to what one wants to do it's a lovely attitude but i think underpinning uh all relationship actually are these two qualities of

39
00:06:54,041 --> 00:06:55,514
gratitude and forgiveness.

40
00:06:56,786 --> 00:06:57,048
Um,

41
00:06:58,716 --> 00:07:25,045
I mean, if we develop this constant sense of gratitude, of being in debt, of wanting to manifest how much we appreciate what's been given to us, I mean, there's always that desire to help, to communicate, to be with somebody in that sort of grateful way.

42
00:07:25,970 --> 00:07:32,223
And you can't have a relationship which at some point isn't going to hurt.

43
00:07:32,423 --> 00:07:36,273
They're going to say something or do something which is going to upset you.

44
00:07:37,053 --> 00:07:42,425
And if you can't let go of that, if that sort of grudge stays within us, a sense of resentment,

45
00:07:42,827 --> 00:07:46,190
And that really undermines the relationship.

46
00:07:46,250 --> 00:07:52,036
It comes out just in the way we speak and in how we ask them to do things.

47
00:07:52,978 --> 00:07:55,920
It's there within our communication.

48
00:07:58,043 --> 00:07:59,423
And I think that's really important.

49
00:07:59,584 --> 00:08:09,874
And I would have thought that most relationships begin to collapse when one or the other side just holds on to these grudges, these resentments.

50
00:08:09,894 --> 00:08:12,716
I remember somebody telling me who was a,

51
00:08:13,978 --> 00:08:20,899
a lawyer for family cases and there was a divorce.

52
00:08:20,939 --> 00:08:21,982
It was quite bitter.

53
00:08:22,744 --> 00:08:28,781
And he kept saying to the husband, there's no point in going to court for this because you will lose.

54
00:08:29,656 --> 00:08:38,649
It'll be a complete waste of time for you to go to court and get all this out in court because you will lose the case, you know.

55
00:08:38,669 --> 00:08:43,356
So he tried to get it across them, but he wanted to go to court.

56
00:08:43,376 --> 00:08:48,644
He wanted somewhere where he could, you know, explain all over the place.

57
00:08:49,427 --> 00:08:54,955
And that's the sort of anger and the bitterness that can come with holding onto resentments.

58
00:08:58,798 --> 00:09:04,888
Just, you know, there's a lovely, I read something quite lovely about this journalist.

59
00:09:04,908 --> 00:09:06,931
She'd gone down in America.

60
00:09:07,032 --> 00:09:10,096
She'd gone down to see how dolphins are trained.

61
00:09:11,138 --> 00:09:23,777
And what she saw was that whenever a dolphin didn't jump through the hoop or play the trick or fail to do the trick, nothing was said, absolutely nothing.

62
00:09:23,857 --> 00:09:53,476
and uh and then they they sort of did the usual routine and the dolphin would complete the trick when the dolphin complete is the trick the trainers jumped up and down with great joy shouting and whooping and making all sorts of great noises so uh she thought well i wonder if this i wonder if this would work on my husband so when she went back home she never criticized him she never said anything but every time he did something that

63
00:09:53,760 --> 00:10:01,248
pleased her, or he did something the way she wanted him to do, she would jump up and down with great joy and blow trumpets.

64
00:10:02,850 --> 00:10:04,591
And he changed completely.

65
00:10:04,652 --> 00:10:07,855
Without knowing it, it was very harmonious.

66
00:10:08,514 --> 00:10:11,337
And then, of course, he went and told her.

67
00:10:11,357 --> 00:10:12,239
She went and told him.

68
00:10:12,259 --> 00:10:21,607
And so he found that also worked, even if it's a consciousness, even if it's a conscious thing that the other person knows what you're doing.

69
00:10:21,587 --> 00:10:49,130
it actually works so this so holding back on criticisms and all that sort of stuff and really rejoicing when the person does something which is uh to your benefit uh seems to have seems to be the trick really getting people to do what you want them to do and the final thing um is of course our spiritual well-being

70
00:10:51,153 --> 00:10:58,484
I mean, obviously, if you're living with somebody who's on your path, then that's a tremendous sort of boost, isn't it?

71
00:10:59,085 --> 00:11:05,354
I mean, I've known people who've taken to the Buddhist path, but their partner really just doesn't like it.

72
00:11:05,374 --> 00:11:06,596
The spouse doesn't like it.

73
00:11:07,096 --> 00:11:08,798
And it's been a point of contention.

74
00:11:09,659 --> 00:11:16,809
But if you happen to be living with somebody who's actually practicing with you, it's obviously a massive support, you know.

75
00:11:17,510 --> 00:11:19,995
And it's the same with any friendship that does it.

76
00:11:20,649 --> 00:11:24,735
And just to sort of end with this lovely quote from the Buddha.

77
00:11:25,417 --> 00:11:37,134
So Ananda, who was with him for the last 20 years of his life as a personal assistant, he always thinks he knows a bit more than he actually does.

78
00:11:38,015 --> 00:11:49,273
And on this occasion, he said to the Buddha, Bhagavan, this is half the spiritual life, good friendship, good companionship, and good comradeship.

79
00:11:50,148 --> 00:12:17,758
the buddha says oh not so ananda not so this is the entire spiritual life that is good friendship good companionship and good comradeship for when someone has a good friend a good companion and a good combat it is to be expected they will develop and cultivate the noble eightfold path so that was his um

80
00:12:17,923 --> 00:12:42,312
understanding of what friendship was you know a good friendship and of course if we remember he was with his five friends when uh you know he he left them uh they all thought he'd gone soft remember he was practicing this um ascetic um asceticism which was basically not eating letting go of the body you know

81
00:12:42,746 --> 00:13:10,323
and he was with five friends five close friends were all practicing together and we all know that uh you know practicing with people in a group is is so much more encouraging than doing it by yourself so um all these points i mean there's there's a lot more of course i'm sure that you could think of it i think of them but um just you know bringing to mind that sense of care

82
00:13:10,708 --> 00:13:13,596
Affection and kindness, especially kindness.

83
00:13:13,677 --> 00:13:14,158
I don't know.

84
00:13:14,177 --> 00:13:21,596
It's a big thing with me that these underlying attitudes of gratitude and forgiveness.

85
00:13:22,522 --> 00:13:47,888
uh and then finally uh just that ability to be with somebody without open to their ideas to their understandings even in conversation even in conversation what if i put aside my ideas you know my views my opinions and open up to what the other one has to say so often we we don't like to do that because they might change our minds

86
00:13:49,740 --> 00:14:00,519
So it's a case of looking at our relationships from this point of view of being with another human being who's like us.

87
00:14:00,739 --> 00:14:04,524
So I'm a human being and you're a human being and just remembering that.

88
00:14:05,265 --> 00:14:13,099
And that I think produces for us that sort of relationship of kindness and care.

89
00:14:14,664 --> 00:14:15,206
Very good.

90
00:14:15,606 --> 00:14:29,990
So I can only hope my words have been of some assistance and I have not caused any confusion and that you will, by your practice of loving-kindness, be fully liberated sooner rather than later.

